motherhood has pivoted me into different experiences — 

the highest and most important of them all is the experience of being present. of tasting and being in the richness of a moment. 

motherhood has taught me that if we focus on and get too caught up in the concept of time, we lose the essence of our experience. we remain stuck in this loop of wishing time stood still and trying to hold on too tightly to what has passed, that we miss (lose) the moment and then we MISS (long for) the moment. 

in what ways are you honoring and just being in the present? being here. now. 

** registration for my first creative workshop soulstice has been extended. we will officially begin january 8th because life and shifts. looking forward to continuing to share more on this offering and to be in community with you all! **

“there is joy here. 
and celebration. 
and love. 
and ocean. 
and sunset. 

there is awakening here. 
and leaving it all behind. 
and stepping into. 

there is healing here. 
and vulnerability. 
and kindred souls. 
and i know you from another life. 

and.” 

i wrote this poem during one of our evening yoga sessions as we stopped to watch the sun set. 

one evening, i cried at how magnificent and miracle and glorious the sun was and how present i was in witnessing its magic. 

the seven spiritual laws of success retreat was many things; sometimes words miss me when i try to describe it but healing and transformational and abundant and joy-full are just a few. 

i am drowning in gratitude for the light of my father and my sister who i shared this experience with. for the beautiful souls that i met — the folks i danced on the beach with under divine moonlight. for the folks who poured into us. for deepak chopra who is an otherworldly and phenomenal being. 

i am crossing the threshold. 
and stepping into a different 
way of being. and stepping 
into a different way of relating 
to my life. and i am sharing it all. 
i am filling cups in ways that
my cup was so beautifully filled. 

and so it is. 
and so it is. 
asè.

i affirm, today — 

the roadblocks and detours encourage my evolution. while the road ahead of me is a mystery, i give myself permission to not need to know what lies ahead. i gather the tools that i need, here and now, that shall support me in the future.

it is all a practice so give yourself grace. 
it is all a practice so give yourself compassion. 
it is all a practice so love yourself through the moments when you feel like you could do better (even though, i’m sure, you’re doing your best). 

i am facilitating a workshop on self-care tomorrow — the discussion will be around the domains of self-care, how we can incorporate more self-care into our lives and the importance of penciling ourselves in. 

let’s continue to release this idea that self-care is selfish and open our minds to the things that can occur when we don’t take care of ourselves. 

self-care can look like many things. 
it can look like — 

reading a book. 
taking a bath. 
writing affirmations. 
setting boundaries. 
saying no. 
meditating. 
potting a plant. 
painting. 
daydreaming. 

what does self-care look like in your life?

a few words to speak to yourself as you continue to move through your day. 

i lead a workshop the other day on self-care and too many people talked about — 

overgiving. 
overproducing. 
not honoring the boundaries they place. 
not resting. 
what is rest and sleep? 
how overwhelming self-care feels 
how social media makes self-care feel inaccessible 

we dove deep and we set a foundation for how to carry for ourselves better. 

i want YOU to know — 

caring for yourself isn’t selfish. 
it is NOT self-indulgent. 
as our ancestor audre lorde tells us so beautifully— 

it is absolutely necessary for our own self-preservation. 

so, remember to love yourself. 
in the ways that only you can love yourself. 

voices from the village — 

how do you love yourself?

your breakdowns can very well be your breakthrough. focus on where the blooming can happen rather than where the crumbling may occur. 

do you remember a time when this wasn’t your truth? 
or maybe it’s not your truth now — but it could be. 

i remember when it wasn’t mine. 
i remember trying so hard to make it so. 
that’s where these words were created. 
in the corners of grief. 
in the unsettled dust of dissatisfaction. 
on the mantle of self-sabotage. 

there was a time when i refused to witness the light that was shining at the end of what felt like a dark and lonely tunnel. 

there was a time when my lack of holding onto hope, deepened the suffering. 

i wrote this in the midst of that. 
because i needed something to hold onto. 
i NEEDED hope. 
i NEEDED a reason to find joy.
i NEEDED something that was going to convince me that there was a light at the end of the tunnel; 
that i just had to clear away the debris to witness it. 

there is a breakthrough on the other side of this, dear one. 

there is a different version of yourself on the other side of this. 

your heart will be healed. 
you will find healing. 

i know it may hurt now and it may be challenging and you just want this season to be behind you — 

but it’s when you’re on the other side.
it’s when you are basking in the sunshine. 
it’s when your life is full of sweet joys. 
it’s when you are dancing in the light of this new version of you that you realize maybe it was worth it.

just hold on a little longer. 
just hold on.

while some folks should absolutely mind the business that pays them, that’s not always the case. 

while some folks should spend their free time sifting and sorting through their baggage instead of trying to peek into yours, they don’t. 

while some folks should focus on how to gain access to their own joy, they don’t. 

none of that has anything to do with you. 

when you make other people’s judgments or opinions of you your business, you pull yourself out of your reality and into this false reality that they have created. 

essentially, you pull yourself out of the expansiveness of what your life has potential to be and into the confinements of a box that you never belonged in.

even then. especially then. 

you are allowed to find joy. 
you are allowed to be in your joy. 
you are allowed to heal through joy.

oh, relationships. 
oh, love. 

you know those moments in love when everything feels like bliss? 
like heaven? like ‘is this too good to be true?’ 
like home? like ‘i love it here.’

you know those moments when love is being reciprocated? 
when it feels like you’re moving with the currant of love rather than against it? 
when love feels easy like sunday morning? 

but what about those moments —
when you’re triggered? 
when love feels like the hardest thing
you’ve ever had to do. 
when moving through and unlearning learned and toxic behaviors feels like work that you’re not ready to do? 

those are the moments this piece was inspired by.

i remember the days when i stood in the way of myself and my healing. 

when i was afraid to let love in. 

because what if i allowed myself to open up, to be vulnerable to the extent that love asks for and i got my heart broken? 

in love, i remember waiting for heartbreak at every corner. 

even in my own healing — 

i had all this trauma and all of these learned behaviors that were attached to me. 
these moments in my life that i had experienced that, for so long, defined me. 

they defined who i was. 
they defined how i moved in the world. 
they defined how i moved in my relationships. 
they defined my very existence. 

but who was i without these things —

without the guards up? 
without the defenses? 
without the limiting beliefs? 
without the toxic traits that i carried? 
without the learned behaviors that weren’t serving me? 

who was i when i finally allowed myself to let go of these things that i believed were protecting me but were actually getting in the way —

of myself. 
of honest and vulnerable relationships. 
of a rich and full life. 
of experiencing joy to its full and unbound capacity. 

who was i outside of these experiences that had defined me for so long? 

who are YOU without them?

“look into the mirror say i love you daily.”

you never had to search in the arms of lovers who couldn’t hold you. 
you never had to search in the hearts of folks who couldn’t love you. 
you never had to search in the eyes or the gaze of folks who couldn’t see you. 

the truth of who you are has always existed within. 
the very essence of you has always existed within.

how do you return to the home within you? 
how do you reclaim the truth that you are a safe space? 
how do you reclaim the knowing that you are a sanctuary? 

what helps you remember that here, with and within yourself, is where you have always belonged.

gentle reminders for your day — 

allow your heart to be your north star. 

allow your heart to guide you, to soothe you, to affirm you. 

allow yourself to escape the (sometimes) jagged landscape of your mind. 

your mind has the ability to create untruths and stories that limit you from seeing your whole self. 

while your heart carries the truth of you are and who you were always meant to be. 

allow yourself to honor. to acknowledge. to tap into. to listen to. to sync up with the truths that your heart is whispering. 

which one is resonating with your heart today?

to the women who are figuring out what that looks like. 

tag a woman who inspires you.

Last week was a week of — 

Moving through and with my feelings;
The deep anxiety. 
The sadness. 
The frustration. 
The disappointment. 
The discouragement. 
And being okay with whatever arose. 

Last week was a week of — 

Pausing. 
Not searching for a solution right away. 
Being in the uncomfortable feelings of 
“The problem” —
Not labeling it a good problem or a bad problem. 
Just allowing it to be. 

Last week was a week of —

Breakthroughs. 
So many breakthroughs. 
Being on the other side of my feelings 
after being in them so deep. 
Being on the other side of “the problem” 
after giving it room to be. 

What I was reminded of — 

Sometimes we just have to be with the ebb. 
And the flow. 
Sometimes we just have to quiet our ego 
and release the reins of control. 
Sometimes we just have to trust that if 
a re-route is to happen; let it. 
Sometimes we just have to that if 
something isn’t for us; move in the 
direction of what is —

And if you don’t have clarity on what that
is exactly, trust that you will.

it can be buried. 
it can be placed on the mantle to collect dusk. 
it can be tucked away in the corner; 
to tend to later. 

but it will always need tending to. 

i have learned that even when i am going through a period of healing, i don’t have to be healing or doing the work all the time. 

i have learned that the work is also done in finding moments of joy. 

i have learned that the work is also done in finding new ways to relate to and be in my life. 

i have learned that the work is also done when i am extending compassion and grace to myself when i am triggered. 

i have learned that i cannot burden myself with a deadline. i am learning to move with the currant rather than against it.

i turn 33 today. 
praise god. 

i woke up to joy and love that knows no conditions. being a mother has opened my heart to so many realizations — 

one of my most cherished realizations is when both of my girls tuck themselves in my arms. 

one settled in the nook of one and the other settled in the nook of the other. 

i thank God for the ability to carry them as they nuzzle close to me as if recalling or remembering that this body used to be home.

that’s how my morning started; cuddling and cradling. 

my husband planting kisses on my face, gazing at me with eyes of love and gratitude. 

he has been in my life for 18 birthdays; we were so in awe of that realization this morning. but, so grateful and so deeply in love.

this morning was the perfect depiction of what i am calling in for this year — love, ease, softness, joy, gratitude, abundance. 

my life is full. 
it feels good. 
it feels in flow. 
and for that, i am grateful.

here are 33 lessons/reflections/musings/affirmations/song lyrics/vows/prayers that i scribbled in my journal this morning; words that have fortified me and carried me the last decade.

1. you know what is best for you, trust that.

2. in this love, you can let go of the disguises. you can remove the armor. you can let your guard down. your heart is safe here.

3. you are the creator of the reality and life you want to live.

4. heartbreak, sadness, grief, anger, frustration. it’s all okay to feel. these feelings don’t define you.

5. don’t abandon the things that bring you joy. even if you do for a moment, your heart will be the compass that leads you back to them.

6. “i can’t save nobody. i put my cape down, sorry. i’m gonna need some boundaries because i’m keeping my peace.” - mayyadda

asé.

forgiveness is about you — 

it is about letting go of the things weighing you down. 
it is about accepting folks for who they are and not who you wish they could be. 
it is about moving forward so you can continue to thrive. 
it is about moving forward to welcome in relationships that are more aligned with you and your life walk. 
it is about letting go so you can give yourself fully to the folks who can love you and who will allow you to love them. 

it is also about forgiving yourself — 
for being hard on yourself when things got hard. 
for being hard on yourself for not knowing what you know now, then. 
for not giving yourself the grace and compassion that you deserve. 

i am currently in a season of forgiving. 
and while it is not easy (no one ever promised it would be),
every day, i feel the burden of not forgiving and letting go being lifted a little more.
